
#
# This is an extended TRIPLE-band version of a Golden Software ASCII Grid file (GSA).
# This file does not contain any geodetically meaningful material, it is constructed
# (mostly) manually, in order to support testing of the Rust Geodesy GSA-reader and
# in particular, its conformance with GDAL's georeferencing conventions:
#
# While GDAL supports the grid "AREA_OR_POINT=Point" convention, its support is based
# on an underlying image native convention of "AREA_OR_POINT=Area".
#
# Numerically, this does not make any difference, as long as one manages the related
# off-by-a-half problem. But fundamentally, it is the difference between interpreting
# the grid values as estimates of areal mean values, georeferenced using a corner of
# that area, interpreted as a cell, or as estimates of point values, georeferenced
# using the coordinates of that exact point.
#
# In geodesy it is (almost) always the latter which is the case, so building the
# GDAL interoperability on GRID, rather than IMAGE formats, significantly reduces the
# risk of off-by-a-half errors: GDAL knows exactly what to do, and represents decades
# of reality hardening, making these easy-to-commit blunders very unlikely in the GDAL
# universe.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# This file is based on the existing SINGLE band gtx file egm96_15_subset.gtx, adding
# two extra bands, offset vertically by approximately 100 m and 200 m, respectively,
# by saying:
#
#    gdal_translate -of GSAG -q gtx\egm96_15_subset.gtx 0
#    gdal_translate -of GSAG -q -scale 29 42 129 142 gtx/egm96_15_subset.gtx 1
#    gdal_translate -of GSAG -q -scale 29 42 229 242 gtx/egm96_15_subset.gtx 2
#    cat 0 1 2 > egm96_15_subset.gsa
#
# In extension to the canonical implementations in Surfer and GDAL, Rust Geodesy's
# GSA reader understands (and ignores) inline and block comments, delineated by the
# sharp ('#') symbol.
#
# It also accepts multiple grids, concatenated into one file, provided their headers
# are geometrically equivalent. Such grids (as the present one) are interpreted as a
# single multiband grid.
#
# Files using these format extensions are obviously not interoperable with other
# software than Rust Geodesy, but they offer a gateway for grid authoring and
# rudimentary documentation, based on arbitrary foundational software. Also, they
# offer a fairly strightforward route for importing gridded data from any of the
# plethora of formats supported by GDAL.
#

